@Node "SYNOPSIS" "Synopsis"

  @{b}How to start WBMakeLink?@{ub}

    @{i}It's SIMPLE!@{ui}
    Just drop it in your WBStartup directory or anywhere else you want
    and double click its icon.
    The settings for WBMakeLink are stored in its Workbench icon.
  
  @{b}What is WBMakeLink?@{ub}

    WBMakeLink adds a menu item to the "Tools" menu of the Workbench screen.
    If you are familiar with the "Make Alias" menu item on Macintosh
    systems, WBMakeLink will feel right at home for you.  Simply select
    an icon (or icons) on the Workbech screen and select "Make Link"
    from the tools menu.  A link to the selected icons will be made,
    and a new icon will be made for the link file.

    If no icon exists for the file that is selected, no link icon will
    be made, unless the "ALWAYSMAKEICON" @{" tooltype " Link "TOOLTYPES"} exists.

@EndNode

@Node "WHYCOPYICON" "Why does WBMakeLink copy the icon?"

  @{b}WBMakeLink copys the icon instead of making a link to the icon.@{ub}

    This is because in order to make the linked icon appear in a
    different snapshotted place than the original icon, it has to
    have a different set of x,y coordinates, which are stored in
    the icon.

    If it didn't, the icon would be placed over the original icon in
    the workbench window, unless the icon was unsnapshoted.

    Even if a link file was created, once you moved the icon and
    snapshotted it, it would be saved as a real file, instead of
    a link.


    If no icon exists for the file that is selected, no link icon will
    be made, unless the "ALWAYSMAKEICON" @{" tooltype " Link "TOOLTYPES"} exists.

@EndNode


