@Node "TOOLTYPES" "Tooltypes"

                     @{b}Description of the icon tooltypes@{ub}

  The following are the tooltypes in which WBMakeLink gets its settings
  from when it is started.

  The tooltypes can be marked out so that they are not defined by placing
  parenthesis around the keyword.  For example (ALWAYSMAKEICON).


  MENUNAME=
    You can set the name that you want to appear in the "Tools" menu.

  ALWAYSMAKEICON
    If this tooltype exists, WBMakeLink will always make an icon for the
    linked file, even if the original file doesn't have an icon.

@EndNode


@Node "DEFAULTS" "Default Settings"

                             @{b}Default Settings@{ub}


  MENUNAME=Make Link

  (ALWAYSMAKEICON)   <--- In other words, it doesn't always make an icon.


@EndNode


@Node "FEATURES" "Features"

                             @{b}WBMakeLink Features@{ub}


  o Uses the "Tools" menu in Workbench.
  o Create file links from workbench, and add's an icon for the link.
  o Configurable menu item name.
  o If you like, it will even create link icons for files with no icons.

@EndNode


@Node "QUITING" "How to quit WBMakeLink"

                       @{b}How to Quit WBMakeLink@{ub}



  1.  Make sure no icons are selected.
      Select "Make Link" from the "Tools" menu in Workbench.
      Select "Quit" from the requester.
  2.  OR send WBMakeLink a CTRL-C.

@EndNode



